<P>The plaintif for that the Arbitrators had giuen that vn|to Strangers (&s;aith h&eacute;e) which &s;hould haue b&eacute;en his and &s;o haue exc&eacute;eded the limits of their authoritie and the tenour of his &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion. The defendant thought him gr&eacute;eued with the greatnes of the &s;um and &s;o both the parties highly di&s;plea&s;ed.</P>
<P>The Arbitrators maintained their awarde and order to be both iu&s;t and rea&s;onable. Fir&s;t for the Defendaunt, they &s;aid they were of duety bond to puni&s;h him vpon good &amp; due proofs made by his Aduer&s;arie of his the vngodly behauiour, where neuerthele&s;&s;e they had qualified his puni&s;hment and the de|maunde by his Aduer&s;ary. As touching the plaintif and the &s;um which h&eacute;e demau~ded by the name and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">earin of a|mends: their an&s;were was that they ment it &s;uch to wit an a|mends and that not only vnto one of them but to them both for they hoped that the Defendaunt by that time h&eacute;e hath pai|ed the two hundred &amp; fiftie pounds wil be better h&eacute;erafter as concerning the like <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ffr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ce and &s;o h&eacute;e hath his amends, but
<PB REF="42"> what or how you would haue b&eacute;en amended by the r<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ceit of &s;o much money paid vnto you: if it might haue app&eacute;er<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d vnto vs: wee verily would haue adiudged it vnto you, but that could w&eacute;e neuer perceiue nor be per&s;waded to beleeue, for w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> neuer heard that honor, vertue, godlynes and the exi&s;timation ther|in are or euer were valued or valuable by money <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">aking, but rather in departing there from, for as the la&s;t doo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">h &s;hew a noble, gentle and a godly hart and mynde: &s;o dooth the fir&s;t argue the mo&s;t vile abiect and ba&s;e&s;t minded per&s;on that e|uer can be &amp; one in whome is vtterly mi&s;pri&s;on of all vertue as wel witne&s;&s;eth S. <HI>Peter</HI> vnto <HI>Simon Magus,</HI> w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">erfore (&s;aid they) we thought that in this di&s;tributio~ which we mean to be your act: you haue vnto the world &s;ufficiently di<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">prooued what&s;oeuer euil your Aduer&s;ary hath purpo&s;ed to bring vpon you as touching your exi&s;timation or good name and haue &s;hewed your &s;elf in very d&eacute;ed &s;uch a man as in the preamble of your declaration you gladly would be taken to be, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">nd &s;uch as if you be not alredy: w&eacute;e verily think that the rec<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">it of all this and ten times as much more will neuer make <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ou, and therfore can be called no mends vnto you in the tak<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ng: but rather in the hone&s;t di&s;tributing therof, which we holde a iu&s;t and rea&s;onable Iudgement in all actions of &s;uch nat<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">re.</P>
<P>&para; With that the two parties drew foorth either o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">hers ob|ligation, &amp; cancelled them bothe, and took hands and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">eparted home great Fr&eacute;ends &s;pite of the Arbitrators and o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> their a|warde, and &s;o ij. Churles were made fr&eacute;ends.</P>
<P>THis tale b&eacute;eing ended, <HI>Pierce Plowman</HI> would <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&eacute;eds ac|quite with an other tale not vnlike. It chaunce<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> one day (quoth h&eacute;e) while I was in my Councellers Cham<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">er in the Inner Temple: there came a woman dwelling about the Strand, and prayed his councell, and what action &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">e might bring again&s;t an other woman a neighbour of hers, that had &s;aid to her in open pre&s;ence of diuers of her neighb<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">urs, that &s;he had already twi&s;e e&s;caped the Gallowes. M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> Lawyer a&s;ked of her if &s;he had neuer in her life pa&s;&s;ed by a pair of Gal+lowes. She an&s;wered yes. So haue I doon (quoth h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">) I thank my God, and that &s;ome time when there haue b&eacute;en a dozen
<PB REF="43"> hanged, and &s;o I think haue you (quoth h&eacute;e). True it is Sir quoth &s;he. Then quoth he, ye cannot recouer for tho&s;e woor|des, for they beare good couller of iu&s;tification, and al&s;o &s;hew that ye haue had better fortune then po&s;&s;ible many a better mans Childe, and &s;o haue I my &s;elf al&s;o. With this an&s;were the good woman held her &s;elf wel apaid, and went her way con+tent.</P>
<P>THen began my tale. There is dwelling in <HI>Holbourne</HI> (quoth I) and that not very far from the place where I doo lye, a certain man whome I haue noted this long time to be a man of &s;trange affection, for b&eacute;eing a man of great wealth and therfore the m&eacute;eter for company, yet if any fr&eacute;end or neighbour require him to goe with them to the Tauern, to the Ale hou&s;e, to the Theater, to y^e Curtain as they tearm it, or to Paris garden or any &s;uch place of expence: he vtter|ly refu&s;eth, &amp; after their return that willed his company: his maner is to go vnto &s;ome one of them, de&s;iring him to tel him truely what h&eacute;e hath &s;pent &s;ince his going foorth, which ha|uing learned at him whether it be a grote or &s;ixpence, more or le&s;&s;e, h&eacute;e goeth &s;traight vnto a Cofer that h&eacute;e hath &s;tanding &s;ecretly in his Chamber, which hath a Til, in the which Til there is a little clift, at the which clift h&eacute;e putteth in a&s;much mony as the partie &s;aid y^t had &s;pent, and this til, h&eacute;e neuer o|peneth vntill the end of the y&eacute;er, &s;o often times h&eacute;e findeth ther in fortie &s;hillings, oft times thr&eacute;e or foure pound or more and this he taketh and be&s;toweth vpon his poore neighbours, and vpon other godly bu&s;ines imployeth it.</P>
<P>And vpon the lid of his Che&s;t is written in great Romain letters, take from thy kinde, and giue to the blinde.</P>
<P>This tale b&eacute;eing ended, the night &s;ome what far rumour Ho&s;+te&s;&s;e warned vs therof and that it was high time to go to bed, which we were all contented to doo &s;auing <HI>Pierce</HI> Plowman, who had yet one other tale to tel, and prayed vs to giue him the hearing, which we graunted him, and then h&eacute;e began.</P>
<P>&para; There is h&eacute;er about (quoth <HI>Pierce</HI>) a Gentleman that hath enlarged his rent but not his land (where in many are very expert at this day) &amp; once vpon a time of my being in his
<PB REF="43"> hou&s;e there came in a poore tenaunt of his, one that ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> b&eacute;en long tenaunt both to his father and others his Aunc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;tors, which poore man pittifully &s;aid vnto him as followeth</P>
<P>Alas Sir (quoth h&eacute;e) in your Fathers and graundf<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">thers dayes I liued wel and kept at the lea&s;t twentie Kine <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">e&s;ides Oxen and hor&s;es, and now through your hard dealing with me I am not able to k&eacute;ep twain.</P>
<P>Wel quoth the Gentleman thou lie&s;t, for I haue b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="2 letters">n bet|ter to th&eacute;e: then euer my Father or Grandfather wa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">, for where by thine owne confe&s;&s;ion in their time thou di<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t k&eacute;ep but twentie Kine: now thou mai&s;t k&eacute;ep two hundre<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> at the lea&s;t, for now (quoth h&eacute;e) through my fr&eacute;end&s;hip thou mai&s;t be the common Neat hearde, and k&eacute;ep al the bea&s;ts in th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> town.</P>
<P>And thus our tales b&eacute;eing all ended: w&eacute;e required <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">he &s;en|tence of our Ho&s;te&s;&s;e therin, &s;h&eacute;e &s;aid that truely in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">er opi|nion the Stranger (meaning m&eacute;e) had tolde the be&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ale and wherby &s;h&eacute;e had gotten mo&s;te Example of edifica<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ion and knowledge, whereby to help and in&s;truct both her &s;elf and others, and giuing m&eacute;e great and hartie thanks therfore: &s;h&eacute;e gaue Iudgement that I &s;hould break my fa&s;t the next day at the charges of her Hu&s;band and <HI>Pierce</HI> Plowman, &s;h&eacute;e &s;aid farther that to that man of whome I tolde the tale: &s;h&eacute;e was Detter, if &s;he knew how to doo him good.</P>
<P>&para; So h&eacute;er w&eacute;e ended, and went to bed, and the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ext day <HI>Pierce</HI> Plowman was vp very early, and called m&eacute;e vp and our Ho&s;te, (as &s;ithens I haue learned his maner is alwaies to doo) gathered vs all together with the re&s;idue of h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">s hou&s;e|holde, mainy, Children and Seruants.</P>
<P>And h&eacute;e him &s;elf red vnto vs a Chapter of the new Te&s;ta|ment, and then w&eacute;e altogether &s;ung the fift&eacute;en P&s;alme of <HI>Da|uid,</HI> and that doon to breakfa&s;t went, and after break<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">a&s;t: I my &s;elf would n&eacute;eds pay the whole charges therof, and bid, (not|with&s;tanding the awarde of our Ho&s;te&s;&s;e and their great in|&s;tance to the contrary.)</P>
<P>And when I would departe: my Ho&s;te and <HI>Pie<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ce</HI> Plow|man would (whether I would or no) bring m&eacute;e on my way to <HI>Donca&s;ter,</HI> and did, and there cau&s;ed m&eacute;e to haue great en|tertainment
<PB REF="44"> without a peny charges for one whole day, and then w&eacute;e took either leaue of other, and departed each of vs toward his owne.</P>
<P>After which departure, vpon the way as I traueled: I re|membred y^e Prophet <HI>Dauid</HI> who &s;aith. <HI>I was glad when it was &s;aid vnto mee, wee &s;hall go into the hou&s;e of the Lord,</HI> which I &s;uppo&s;e be neuer ment by a co~mon Inne or ho&s;terie, where neuerthele&s;&s;e I may &s;afely &s;ay I found it. And therfore full true it is y^e <HI>Ouid</HI> &s;aith, there is oftentimes a good fi&s;h in a wa|ter where a man would little think. W&eacute;e boa&s;t much of ciui|litie and nurture in the South partes of this land, namely in London, and di&s;prai&s;e and di&s;pi&s;e the North as rude and vn|ciuil, but &s;urely for mine owne parte (that am a Southern|man and borne in Kent) to &s;peak indifferently for any thing that euer I haue found in all my trauel in both the partes: I cannot &s;&eacute;e nor know why the Northern People &s;hould not rather pittie vs then enuie vs concerning either Godly|nes, Vertue or good maners, for h&eacute;er I haue &s;poken of the ba|&s;e&s;t kinde of People, wherby it may partly approoue what hope there is of the Gentlemen, merchants and them of the good Townes and Citties, for who&s;e &s;akes and generally for all others I vndertook to gather and to report this little Con|ference, and with Gods help and fauour haue doon it as n&eacute;er accordant to the trueth as I could, neither adding therto nor taking there from, the de&s;ire wherof cau&s;ed m&eacute;e to take the le&s;&s;er Iournies homewarde and to write it by parcells at my Innes lea&s;t I might haue forgotten it.</P>
<P>And h&eacute;erin I prote&s;t, that I haue neither flattered nor be|lyed any man, for my meaning is trueth and the commen|dation therof, and therin is no flattery, for &s;urelie if I haue flattered any body: it is mine owne &s;elf in y^t, that where be|fore I was per&s;waded that pride had vtterly corrupted this whole common welth and had clean ouer &s;pred it with his ge+neration of all vngodlynes and wickednes wherof all times and ages doo agr&eacute;e him to be the father: &s;ithence this Iourney I begin to hope y^t God wil haue mercy vpon vs, and hath and that h&eacute;e hath re&s;erued vnto him &s;elf a remnaunt as h&eacute;e did
<PB REF="44"> in the time of <HI>Elias,</HI> for who&s;e &s;akes h&eacute;e will &s;pare the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">e&s;t as h&eacute;e offered vnto <HI>Abraham</HI> touching <HI>Sodome</HI> and <HI>Gomo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ra.</HI></P>
<P>Therfore the intent of this my collection thus <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">ppea|ring: I refer my &s;elf to the iudgement of them to who&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> ha~ds it &s;hal h&eacute;erafter come, de&s;iring their good woord in reco<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">pence therof, and al&s;o of my long and weary Iourney wherof this labour was mine only rewarde.</P>
<P>Be&s;&eacute;eching Almightie God of his great mercie <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">nd cle|mency to graunt vnto the &s;ame no wur&s;&s;e effect then <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> haue ment therin, and that by the Appo&s;tles councel, we m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">y con|&s;ider that w&eacute;e are but &s;trangers and pilgrimes h&eacute;er i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter"> earth, and that there after w&eacute;e may order our liues and con<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">er&s;ati|on longing for our owne Cuntrie, content to &s;uffer, a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">d to for beare and glad to heare or &s;&eacute;e the thing that may <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&eacute;e for our edifying, learning and knowledge to b&eacute;e the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="KEYERS" EXTENT="1 letter">&eacute;e|ter and better welcome into our Cuntrie which is the Heauenly <HI>Ieru&s;alem</HI> whether God for Chri&s;tes &s;ake bring vs all Amen.</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
<CLOSER>Laus Deo.</CLOSER>
